The following code is intended to print all integers from `1` to `n` inclusive, but it contains a bug. Which change corrects the bug?

```java
int i = 1;
while (i < n) {
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
}
```

Determine the values of `lo` and `hi` after the following code finishes executing.

```java
int lo = 1;
int hi = 10;
while (lo < hi) {
    lo++;
    hi--;
}
```

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
int i = 2;
int total = 1;
while (i <= 4) {
    total *= i;
    i++;
}
System.out.println(total);
```

Which of the following best describes the behavior of the code below?

```java
int count = 0;
int n = 1;
while (n < 10) {
    if (n % 2 == 0) {
        count++;
    }
}
System.out.println(count);
```

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
int n = 523;
int result = 0;
while (n > 0) {
    result = result * 10 + n % 10;
    n /= 10;
}
System.out.println(result);
```

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
String s = "banana";
int i = 0;
int count = 0;
while (i < s.length()) {
    if (s.substring(i, i + 1).equals("a")) {
        count++;
    }
    i++;
}
System.out.println(count);
```

